<br />
<br />I'm looking at all my options I can use.  Just going straight NES is definately the cheapest and simplest in terms of use.  
<br />
<br />A tiny PC with an emulator is definately the most versatile, but a bit more expensive (I have a couple old NES's, I would need to purchase the hardware for a small PC, including an SSD and an OS).  Plus I would need to come up with a way to make loading the emulator and games easy.  I could just have the emulator boot on startup, but the emulators I have used have had a somewhat clunky interface, but that was all a while ago and I didn't really get into it to much, so there may be better ones out there.  Also since I will be entering car shows I want to keep things as legal as possible, and I don't know if the software falls under abandonware or what.  I'm sure I won't have any issues so this isn't a big concern to me really. The nice thing with a tiny PC is that it is probably the easiest to integrate into the car, no need to cut slots for cartridges, just a power button and some USB ports for the interface.
<br />
<br />Definately need to think about it some more, but I just want to explore my options.</div>

